    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 4, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🐋 DeepSeek V4: One Trillion Parameters, $5.2 Million, Open Weights\n\nChina's DeepSeek released V4 — a one-trillion-parameter Mixture-of-Experts model with fully open weights under Apache 2.0. Training cost: an estimated $5.2 million. Comparable US frontier models cost somewhere north of $100 million.\n\n- **The specs:** 1T parameters total, ~32B activated per token (MoE efficiency), 94.7% on HumanEval, competitive with Claude Opus and GPT-5 on coding and reasoning benchmarks. Multimodal: text, image, video.\n- **The open-weights catch:** Apache 2.0 means anyone can download, fine-tune, and deploy it commercially — no API fees, no terms of service, no kill switch. Along with Qwen 3.5, it's now among the most capable open-weight models ever built.\n\n*A $5.2M model that trades blows with $100M+ frontier models, released free. US AI labs are taking notes — or pretending not to.*\n\n**Sources:** [Mule AI Blog](https://muleai.io/blog/2026-03-03-deepseek-v4-open-source-ai-revolution/) | [NxCode Specs](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news/deepseek-v4-release-specs-benchmarks-2026) | [Particula Tech](https://particula.tech/blog/deepseek-v4-qwen-open-source-ai-disruption)\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Google's TurboQuant Compresses AI Memory 6x — and Wrecked Chip Stocks Doing It\n\nGoogle Research unveiled TurboQuant, an AI memory compression algorithm that shrinks the key-value cache from 16 bits to 3 bits per value — a 6x reduction — with no measurable accuracy loss. Training-free, drop-in compatible with existing inference pipelines.\n\n- **What it actually does:** the KV cache is one of the most expensive parts of running large models. Compressing it 6x while speeding up attention by 8x means dramatically lower RAM requirements and compute costs — potentially cutting inference costs by 50% or more.\n- **The market reaction:** Micron, Samsung, and SK Hynix shares dropped sharply on the news. DDR5 memory prices have fallen 15–30% in weeks. When Google makes AI more memory-efficient, memory chipmakers feel it immediately.\n\n*Google invented \"Pied Piper\" (the internet is already calling it that) and the RAM industry had a bad week. The paper drops at ICLR in late April.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/25/google-turboquant-ai-memory-compression-silicon-valley-pied-piper/) | [VentureBeat](https://venturebeat.com/infrastructure/googles-new-turboquant-algorithm-speeds-up-ai-memory-8x-cutting-costs-by-50) | [The Next Web](https://thenextweb.com/news/google-turboquant-ai-compression-memory-stocks)\n\n---\n\n## 🦾 Tesla Is Repurposing Its Car Factory to Build Optimus (Target: 1 Million Robots/Year)\n\nTesla confirmed it is converting assembly lines at its Fremont, California factory in Q2 2026 to produce Optimus Gen 3 humanoid robots. The stated target is 1 million units per year at scale, with the first production line expected operational before end of 2026.\n\n- **The hardware update:** Gen 3 hands feature 50 actuators per hand and 22 degrees of freedom — enabling over 3,000 discrete manipulation tasks. The robot body remains Gen 2; the hands are the meaningful leap.\n- **The uncomfortable caveat:** Musk confirmed on the Q4 2025 earnings call that as of February, no Optimus units are doing \"useful work\" — they're still in data collection mode. The gap between \"repurposing a factory\" and \"a robot that does useful work\" is the entire product.\n\n*Tesla is betting a car factory on humanoid robots that don't do useful work yet. Ambitious is one word for it.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tesla Optimus Updates](https://teslarefer.com/blog/tesla-optimus-robot-news) | [Standard Bots](https://standardbots.com/blog/tesla-robot) | [Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/04/04/prediction-ai-robotics-will-be-a-375-billion-indus/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏃 The AI Model Release Cycle Is Now Running Faster Than Anyone Can Track\n\nApril 2026 is shaping up to be an extraordinary month: GPT-5.4 (with a \"Thinking\" reasoning variant) just shipped, GPT-5.5 (\"Spud\") completed pre-training on March 24 and is expected within weeks, and xAI launched a new multi-agent architecture with Grok 4.20 in the same window.\n\n- **GPT-5.4's headline number:** it scored 75.0% on OSWorld-Verified desktop task benchmarks — the first model to formally surpass human-level performance on that test. That is not a benchmark researchers talk about at dinner parties; it measures real computer use.\n- **The velocity problem:** GPT-5.3 shipped, then 5.4, and 5.5 is already baked. Anthropic, Google, xAI, and DeepSeek are all in the same release window. Keeping track of which model is \"best\" is now a full-time job — which is probably the point.\n\n*The model release cadence now has more versions per quarter than some software products ship in a year. Nobody could have predicted this. (Everyone predicted this.)*\n\n**Sources:** [OpenAI GPT-5.4](https://openai.com/index/introducing-gpt-5-4/) | [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/03/05/openai-launches-gpt-5-4-with-pro-and-thinking-versions/) | [devFlokers](https://www.devflokers.com/blog/ai-news-last-24-hours-april-2026-model-releases-breakthroughs)"
